<article>
    <h1>Jew&#xAD;eller fined for fail&#xAD;ing to re&#xAD;port $20,000 cash sale</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200812/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-12"><time>2020-08-12</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline">Do&#xAD;minic Low dom&#xAD;low@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Even af­ter a cus­tomer paid jew­eller Poh Heng more than $20,000 in cash from his bag and pock­ets, it did not raise the alarm with the au­thor­i­ties about the trans­ac­tion.</p>
    <p>The cash was even­tu­ally re­vealed to be part of crim­i­nal pro­ceeds from a scam that cheated gov­ern­ment agency Skill­sFu­ture Sin­ga­pore (SSG) out of al­most $40 mil­lion.</p>
    <p>The cus­tomer, Andy Quek, turned out to be a mem­ber of the syndicate be­hind the scam.</p>
    <p>Poh Heng was con­victed yes­ter­day over its fail­ure to sub­mit a cash trans­ac­tion re­port to the au­thor­i­ties, the first case of its kind here.</p>
    <p>It was fined $9,000 af­ter plead­ing guilty to one charge un­der the Cor­rup­tion, Drug Traf­fick­ing and Other Se­ri­ous Crimes (Con­fis­ca­tion of Ben­e­fits) Act.</p>
    <p>Based on reg­u­la­tions in­tro­duced un­der the Act in 2014, deal­ers in pre­cious stones and/or pre­cious met­als are re­quired to sub­mit such a re­port to the au­thor­i­ties if they en­ter into a sin­gle cash trans­ac­tion with a cus­tomer worth more than $20,000.</p>
    <p>They have to do so within 15 business days af­ter the trans­ac­tion.</p>
    <p>Of­fend­ers who fail to sub­mit the re­port when re­quired may be jailed for up to two years and/or fined up to $20,000.</p>
    <p>Court doc­u­ments state that Quek pur­chased sev­eral pieces of jew­ellery – in­clud­ing two di­a­mond bracelets – worth a to­tal of $28,078 from Poh Heng on Oct 7, 2017.</p>
    <p>The Skill­sFu­ture scam in­volved sub­mit­ting bo­gus claims for sub­si­dies on train­ing cour­ses to SSG, which over­sees the Skill­sFu­ture ini­tia­tive aimed at pro­mot­ing life­long learn­ing among Sin­ga­pore­ans.</p>
    <p>The syndicate used nine shell com­pa­nies to sub­mit a to­tal of 8,386 fraud­u­lent course fee grant ap­pli­ca­tions and 8,391 claims to SSG be­tween May and Oc­to­ber 2017.</p>
    <p>SSG even­tu­ally paid about $39.9 mil­lion for the grants and claims.</p>


</article>

